## Report: Question Answers

---

### Part 1.1 — JAX-RS Resource Lifecycle and Thread Safety

**Question:** Explain the default lifecycle of a JAX-RS Resource class. Is a new instance created per request or treated as a singleton? How does this impact in-memory data management?

**Answer:**

JAX-RS by default generates a new instance of each resource class with each incoming HTTP request. This is referred to as request-scoped lifecycle. Although this design has a thread-safe instance level, because every request is a separate operation on a separate object, it poses a significant difficulty in managing in-memory shared data.
Provided that data was stored as instance fields within a resource class, each new request would result in a totally empty data set since a new object is being created every time. To overcome this, all data in this application is stored in the DataStore class in the form of ConcurrentHashMap fields which are static. These maps are static and exist on the class level and last the lifetime of the application, regardless of the instances of resources.

ConcurrentHashMap was selected in place of a regular HashMap since there can be various HTTP requests concurrently on different threads. A normal HashMap is not thread-safe - simultaneous reads and writes may result in corruption of data or race. ConcurrentHashMap automatically manages internal locking, which keeps data integrity without the need to explicitly block synchronisation.


---

### Part 1.2 — HATEOAS and Hypermedia-Driven Design

**Question:** Why is HATEOAS considered a hallmark of advanced RESTful design? How does it benefit client developers compared to static documentation?

**Answer:**

The concept of HATEOAS, or Hypermedia as the Engine of Application State, is that responses to API be accompanied with links to other related actions and resources, enabling the clients to explore the whole API dynamically starting with a single point.
The discovery endpoint of this API, GET /api/v1, will respond with a resources map with URLs to /rooms and /sensors. A client that gets this reply will not be required to know these URLs beforehand, it can discover and trace them on-the-fly.

HATEOAS has various benefits as compared to fixed documentation. First, it minimizes coupling — clients do not encode URLs, thus enabling the server to alter endpoint paths without breaking clients who use the links. Second, it is self-documenting - a developer can navigate the whole API using links without any external documentation. Third, it enhances maintainability - as the API changes, all that is required is to update the links in the discovery response and have all the clients automatically redirect.


---

### Part 2.1 — ID-only vs Full Object Returns

**Question:** When returning a list of rooms, what are the implications of returning only IDs versus returning full room objects?

**Answer:**

Sending only IDs is bandwidth-friendly but requires the client to issue N further HTTP requests, or one request per room, to get the information about each resource. This is referred to as the N+1 problem and can considerably impair the performance at scale, adding latency and server load.
Full-object returns consume greater bandwidth per response, but provide all the data required in one round trip. This makes it less complex on the client-side, and in general suited to collections of medium size like a room list on a campus.
This API provides complete room objects in response to GET /rooms which is suitable since the size of data is expected to be large. In case of very large datasets, a hybrid method that combines pagination and optional field projection (through query parameters) would be more scalable.


---

### Part 2.2 — Idempotency of DELETE

**Question:** Is the DELETE operation idempotent in your implementation? Justify by describing what happens when the same DELETE request is sent multiple times.

**Answer:**

Yes, in this implementation, DELETE is an idempent operation. Idempotency implies that the server state remains the same following the initial request, and following any multiple identical requests.
The first request to DELETE /rooms/HALL-101 with the room present is sent, the room is deleted and a 204 No Content response is sent. When the identical request is re-sent, the room does not exist in the system anymore, and 404 Not Found is sent. Although the HTTP status code varies on the first and the second call, the server state is the same after the first and the second call the room is not available. This meets the REST idempotency definition, which is defined based on server state, rather than response codes.


---

### Part 3.1 — @Consumes and Media Type Mismatch

**Question:** Explain the technical consequences if a client sends data in a format other than application/json to a method annotated with @Consumes(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON).

**Answer:**

A resource method that is annotated with @Consumes(Mediatype.APPLICATION_JSON), JAX-RS reads the Content-Type header of all incoming requests and then call the method. In case the value of the header is not matched, say, text/plain or application/xml, JAX-RS is unable to identify a corresponding resource method and sends out HTTP 415 Unsupported Media Type by default.

This is rejected on the framework level even before application code has the opportunity to run. The method body is never entered into. This inbuilt contract enforcement guarantees that the resource approach obtains the data it can handle, rather than risking bad or unforeseen input shapes without having to be validated by manual scrutiny within each approach.


---

### Part 3.2 — @QueryParam vs Path Parameter for Filtering

**Question:** Why is the query parameter approach generally considered superior to path-based filtering for searching collections?

**Answer:**

Resource identifier consists of path parameters, e.g., /sensors/type/CO2. Their application in filtering would mean that the type of resource represented by CO2 sensors is fundamentally dissimilar, which is architecturally unsound. REST does not consider the path to be a filtering mechanism; rather it is the identity of a resource.

Query parameters Query parameters can be optional parameters like /sensors?type=CO2 which are optional parameters used on the same collection of resources. The reason why they are better in filtering is because of a number of reasons. To start with, they are optional by nature - the same endpoint receives both filtered and unfiltered requests. Second, they can be built in a natural manner, e.g. they can be built in multiple filters together, e.g. ?type=CO2&status=ACTIVE. Third, they leave the identity of resources the same, i.e. /sensors will always be the sensor collection no matter what filters are used. Fourth, they conform to HTTP caching standards, since query strings are highly known to proxies and CDNs.


---

### Part 4.1 — Sub-Resource Locator Pattern

**Question:** Discuss the architectural benefits of the Sub-Resource Locator pattern compared to defining every nested path in one controller class.

**Answer:**

Sub-Resource Locator pattern enables a resource class to delegate the responsibility of a nested path to another, special-purpose class. SensorResource in this API receives all the requests to /sensors, and provides a locator mechanism to pass /sensors/{ sensorId / readings to SensorReadingResource.

In the absence of this pattern, all nested endpoints (as well as all reading operations) would be declared within SensorResource, forming a large, highly-coupled class, which is a violation of the Single Responsibility Principle. These monolithic controllers are hard to maintain, test and extend as an API expands to dozens of nested resources.
The locator pattern addresses this by assigning each resource level a distinct class having a single clear responsibility. The sensor collection is handled by SensorResource. SensorReadingResource is a reading history manager, which is specific to a sensor context. Development, testing, and modification of each class is possible. This is similar to Java EE and enterprise application dealing with complexity by delegation and separation of concerns.


---

### Part 5.2 — HTTP 422 vs HTTP 404 for Missing References

**Question:** Why is HTTP 422 often considered more semantically accurate than 404 when the issue is a missing reference inside a valid JSON payload?

**Answer:**

The HTTP 404 Not Found response means that the necessary resource or endpoint was not found. It is correct when a client makes a request to a URL which is not available in the server.
HTTP 422 Unprocessable Entity is used to show that the server has received the request and the payload is syntactically correct, but the content is not semantically correct. In case a client dispatches a properly structured JSON body to register a sensor with a roomId that is not available, the endpoint is available and the structure of the data is sound, the issue is a broken reference in the data.
In such a case, it would be incorrect to return 404 - this would imply that the /sensors endpoint is not available, which is incorrect. By sending back 422, it is correct to communicate that the request was being received and interpreted but the business logic could not be fulfilled since there is no such resource being referenced. This detail aids client programmers in knowing the exact nature of the bug and in what manner to correct it.


---

### Part 5.4 — Cybersecurity Risks of Exposing Stack Traces

**Question:** From a cybersecurity standpoint, explain the risks of exposing internal Java stack traces to API consumers.

**Answer:**

There are a number of severe security threats in exposing raw Java stack traces to clients.
First, stack traces expose the internal package and class structure of the application and provide attackers with an in-depth map of the codebase architecture. Second, they divulge library names and version numbers - an attacker can match them with the published vulnerability databases like the CVE to determine the known exploits against the specific versions. Third, they can have server file paths that give the deployment directory hierarchy, which can be used to create focused path traversal or file inclusion attacks. Fourth, they disclose the flow of logic and variables, which are useful to attackers to comprehend how data is processed and where individuals can inject.
This API uses a global ExceptionMapper to all Throwable objects, which sends a generic 500 response with a non-technical and safe message. The actual exception is captured on the server with the help of the java.util.logging.Logger, so that administrators can see it without having to go to the client.


---

### Part 5.5 — JAX-RS Filters for Cross-Cutting Concerns

**Question:** Why is it advantageous to use JAX-RS filters for logging rather than inserting Logger.info() statements into every resource method?

**Answer:**

Entering Logger.info() statements manually into each resource method is monotonous and has a high risk of errors and violates the DRY - Don't Repeat Yourself - concept. In case logging behaviour should be altered, each and every method will have to be changed separately, which adds to the risk of inconsistencies.
The pattern of cross-cutting concern is applied by JAX-RS filters. One filter class that is both a ContainerRequestFilter and ContainerResponseFilter is used to automatically intercept all incoming requests and outgoing responses, whatever resource method they are sent to. Logging is used consistently in all the locations of API.
It is also better maintainable, since it is easy to enable or disable logging, alter the log format, or to add extra context, just by changing the filter class. It also maintains resource methods free and aimed at their main task of dealing with business logic and not muddled up by infrastructure issues such as logging, authentication, or metrics gathering.
